      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Support Ultra thinking for the native Codex runtime",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds `ultra` as a first-class thinking level for OpenClaw's **native Codex app-server runtime** when the live Codex model catalog advertises that level.\n\nThis is intentionally not a generic `ultra -> max` alias. Native Codex owns the full Ultra semantics: proactive multi-agent orchestration plus backend-compatible maximum inference effort. Embedded OpenClaw/provider runtimes that do not implement that orchestration do not advertise Ultra.\n\nLegacy aliases remain stable: `ultrathink` continues to normalize to `high`; only explicit `ultra` selects the new tier.\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nOpenAI Codex PR <https://github.com/openai/codex/pull/29899> defines Ultra as a user-facing orchestration level:\n\n- Codex Core selects `MultiAgentMode::Proactive`.\n- Codex injects proactive delegation instructions and owns native sub-agent execution.\n- At inference boundaries, Codex maps Ultra to the backend-compatible `max` effort.\n\nTherefore OpenClaw should pass explicit `ultra` unchanged to the native Codex app-server, not flatten it to `max` itself. Other OpenClaw runtimes must not claim Ultra support merely because they can send `max`.\n\n## Changes\n\n- Add `ultra` to canonical thinking-level/session types needed to carry a native Codex selection.\n- Preserve `ultrathink -> high` for backwards compatibility; explicit `ultra` is required.\n- Expose Ultra only from the native Codex provider profile when live app-server discovery advertises it.\n- Pass `effort: \"ultra\"` through native Codex `turn/start` and collaboration-mode settings.\n- Keep embedded OpenClaw/OpenAI/Google/Anthropic provider profiles Ultra-free unless they separately implement equivalent orchestration semantics.\n- Add tests for normalization, Codex profile discovery, native request payloads, unsupported-runtime rejection/clamping, and legacy alias behavior.\n- Update thinking-level documentation with the native-Codex-only scope.\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Official semantics\n\nOpenAI Codex PR <https://github.com/openai/codex/pull/29899> implements Ultra in Codex Core. Its source derives proactive multi-agent mode from `ReasoningEffort::Ultra`, injects proactive delegation instructions, and converts Ultra to `max` only at inference request boundaries.\n\n### Real configured-provider behavior (sanitized)\n\nCodex CLI 0.142.4 was configured with:\n\n```toml\nmodel = \"gpt-5.6-sol\"\nmodel_reasoning_effort = \"ultra\"\n```\n\nLive model discovery advertised:\n\n```text\ngpt-5.6-sol: low, medium, high, xhigh, max, ultra\n```\n\nA real ephemeral read-only turn completed successfully:\n\n```text\n$ codex exec --ephemeral --skip-git-repo-check --sandbox read-only --json \\\n    'Reply exactly with ULTRA_OK_1424 and nothing else.'\n...\nitem.completed: ULTRA_OK_1424\nturn.completed\n```\n\nThis proves the native Codex 0.142.4 runtime accepts and executes the Ultra selection. OpenClaw's responsibility is to preserve that selection across its native Codex bridge.\n\n### OpenClaw validation\n\nThe revised branch passed:\n\n```text\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs \\\n  src/auto-reply/thinking.test.ts \\\n  src/llm/model-utils.test.ts \\\n  src/config/config.schema-regressions.test.ts \\\n  extensions/codex/provider.test.ts \\\n  extensions/codex/src/app-server/thread-lifecycle.test.ts\n\n# 198 focused tests passed, including 89 native Codex provider/turn tests\n\npnpm tsgo:core       # passed\npnpm tsgo:core:test  # passed\n```\n\nAdditional OpenAI/Anthropic/Google/provider-stream safety suites passed after verifying that non-Codex profiles do not expose Ultra and stale internal Ultra values are handled defensively rather than forwarded as a claimed feature.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- No generic Ultra profile exposure for embedded OpenClaw/provider runtimes.\n- No claim that `max` alone is equivalent to Ultra. Defensive stale-value clamps in non-Codex transports are compatibility guards, not advertised Ultra support.\n- No reimplementation of Codex proactive multi-agent policy inside OpenClaw; the native Codex app-server owns that behavior.\n",
        "branch": "feat/ultra-thinking-level",
